`crates/steno/tests/` is the integration-test surface for the whole `steno` crate: parsing (`parse_source`, `parse_template`), the two-pass expansion pipeline (`expand_counts`/Pass A, `expand_types_one`/Pass B), the three output renderers (`render_plain`, `render_smart`, `build_snippets`, plus the `@literal`-block struct emitter), stroke primitives (`parse_stroke`/`render_stroke`/`count_bank`/`apply_count`), the editor-simulation/serialization layer, and the nvim Lua plugin. A caller depending on this crate can trust these tests as the executable spec for exact output byte-strings and error-message substrings across all of those stages.

The dominant cross-file coupling is the repo-root `dict.steno` corpus: `blocks.rs`, `expand.rs`, `expand_types.rs`, `parse_source.rs`, `render.rs`, `smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`, and `stroke_order.rs` all load it independently via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../../dict.steno` and hardcode assertions against specific strokes (`STKWR-PBGS/...`, `STKWR-RBGT/S`, `STKWR-BGS`, etc.) and corpus-wide counts (entry totals, `>1000` dictionary keys, zero collisions). Editing `dict.steno` — renaming a stroke, changing a count/arity, adding/removing an `@noarg` type — can break tests in several of these files simultaneously and silently (many use `.unwrap()`, so failures are panics, not descriptive assertions); a change there should be grepped across all eight files, not just the one being edited. Moving the crate relative to the repo root breaks all of them the same way.

One specific corpus mutation already happened and is handled identically in two places: `STKWR-LT` was repurposed (now a `let` binding), so both `smart.rs` and `snippet.rs` independently hand-construct a standalone `TypedEntry` (`template_literal()`/`terminal_entry`) to keep covering the old `` `${%0}` `` template-literal case outside the corpus — anyone changing `TypedEntry`/`Entry`/`EntryFlags`'s layout must update both constructions in lockstep.

Pipeline order is reflected in file dependency direction, not code dependency: `parse_source.rs`/`parse_template.rs` pin the grammar and error text that `expand.rs` (Pass A) builds on, which `expand_types.rs` (Pass B) builds on in turn, which `render.rs`/`smart.rs`/`snippet.rs`/`blocks.rs` all consume via `expand_dict`. `stroke.rs` and `stroke_order.rs` both exercise `parse_stroke`/`render_stroke` but from opposite angles: `stroke.rs` is the round-trip/error-message spec, `stroke_order.rs` uses the same functions as a linter to catch mis-ordered stroke keys in the real corpus that would otherwise parse silently. `editor.rs` and `nvim_plugin.rs` are the outliers with no `dict.steno` dependency — `editor.rs` tests `interpret`/`Behaviors` purely synthetically, and `nvim_plugin.rs` spawns real headless Neovim against the checked-in Lua plugin, the only place plugin-level snippet-expansion behavior (e.g. blank `${0}` exit lines, sentinel-wrapping of only terminal strokes) is checked.